SummaryOfEvents: The ore carrier Marika, loaded with 139,913 tons of pelletized iron ore out of Seven Islands, Quebec, Canada, Gulf of St.Lawrence, bound for The Netherlands, sank at about 14:00 hrs Saturday 1 January 1994, in position Latitude 46 degrees 52.3 minutes North, Longitude 33 degrees 31.0 minutes West. The crew of 36 is assumed to have perished.

Location: Off de New South Wales coast
SummaryOfEvents:
The New Zealand registered roll on/roll off, gas turbine/electric ship Union Rotorua was about 27 miles south of Sydney Heads, en route for Melbourne, when a fire broke out in the gas turbine house. 

It was established that the seat of the fire was in one of the cubicles of the 6.6 kilovolt switchboard, which distributed power from the gas turbine generator to the propulsion motors and auxiliary electrical systems. 

Initial attempts to fight the fire with extinguishers proved to be ineffective and a decision was made to utilise the fixed fire fighting medium and flood the space with CO2. 

This was effective in extinguishing the fire. With the high voltage switchboard out of commission, the ship was towed to Sydney, where it remained for three months undergoing repairs.

Early on the morning of 29 December 1993, the Australian offshore supply ship Shelf Supporter was discharging a deck cargo of empty skips and a container to North Rankin A platform, 70 miles north-west of Dampier. The weather was fine with the wind from the south-west at 20 knots. 
The Master was manoeuvring the ship, maintaining position, from the after end of the bridge, looking out over the cargo deck. 
Seas were breaking over the stern, but conditions were not such as to cause the cancellation of cargo operations. 
While a skip was being hoisted to the platform the two-man deck watch aboard Shelf Supporter decided to re-spool a wire used to secure the cargo, onto the winch. While this wire was being released from a block, a sea broke over the stern. Despite a warning from the Master, one of the two men on deck was crushed between the ships's own rubbish skip and an empty skip when it was moved by the seawater.

Location: Off Wednesday Island, in the Torres strait
SummaryOfEvents:
On 12 July 1997, the Indian flag bulk carrier Dakshineshwar was on a loaded, northbound passage through the inner route of the Great Barrier Reef, from Hay Point to the east coast of India with a cargo of coal. A licensed Reef Pilot was in charge of the navigation. 
At about 21:00 hours, the ship passed between Alert Patches and OG Rock at the eastern end of the Prince of Wales Channel, Torres Strait, and settled on a course of about 270. The ship's speed over the previous hour had been 12 knots. 
At about 21:11 hours, the ship was abeam of Ince Point and the Pilot saw that the Global Positioning System display showed a speed of 10.5 knots. About three minutes later the Pilot, who had moved to the port bridge wing, heard an alarm or some alerting device ringing on the bridge and he went to investigate. As he got close to the centre line he glanced at the helm indicator and engine room tachometer. The helm indicator showed that full starboard rudder had been applied and the tachometer showed zero revolutions. The ship's head had been paying off to port and the rate of turn increased rapidly as the ship closed with Wednesday Island to the western side of Ince Point. 
The ship's speed had slowed to about 6.5 knots when the engine was restarted. The Pilot had to make a quick decision and decided to maintain full starboard rudder and ordered emergency full ahead revolutions to maximise the rate of turn to starboard. The ship reached a heading of 172, before starting to turn to starboard. At about 21:20 hours, Dakshineshwar grounded in position 10 30.4° South 142 17.9° East, with Ince Point Light bearing 100 x 0.85 of a mile.

Location: Shetlands Islands, southern approaches to Lerwiick Harbour, 250 m SE of Bressay Light

SummaryOfEvents:
In the earlier hours of 29 October 1993, the offshore supply ship Pacific Commander manœuvred stern-to the semi-submersible drilling rig Atwood Falcon to back-load some sections of casing. The master  was advised the cargo operation would of short duration and, as a result, he chose not to use an anchor, making fast with two lines aft and maintaining position at right angles to the rig, with the bow thruster. 
After the planned cargo operation was completed and some further equipment transferred, Atwood Falcon then decided to take the opportunity to top up with cement from Pacific Commander, thereby extending the cargo operation significantly. Weather conditions were good and the Master continued to maintain position by use of the bow thruster. In the early afternoon, the Mate was unable to maintain the position and the Master decided to suspend operations and let go. During the operation of letting go, a nylon mooring line, jammed on the bitts, parted under strain, injuring the Mate.

The Baltic Link took on timber and paper products in Gävle from 27 to 29 September 1993. Finally, a consignment of insulating (porous) fibreboard sheets, which will be referred to as softboard, was taken on board and placed aft on below the main deck. The vessel sailed form Hallstavik on 30 September at 14:30 hours bound for Hartlepool, England. At 03:30 hours on 1 October, a smoke alarm was received from the main deck hold. the ship was then approximately 20 nautical miles north of Gotland. 
When the crew had assembled on the bridge, the ship's carbon-dioxide plant on the main deck was activated. The Stockholm Radio Marine Rescue Coordination Centre (MRCC) was alerted. Later on, the Tingstäde Radio Marine Rescue Subcentre (MRSC) took over.  

Equipped with breathing apparatus, members of the crew then inspected the hold and discovered that part of the fibreboard consignment was smouldering. The ship then anchored in Kappelshamnsviken off the island of Gotland.

Smoke divers from the Gotland Rescue Services were put on board by helicopter while the ship lay in Kappelshamnsviken. It was then moved to the quay at Storugns.

When additional carbon dioxide had been supplied, fire-fighting was started on 3 October using smoke divers. That evening, an accident occurred in which a smoke diver returning from his shifts lost contact with his colleague, fell over on the main deck and remained lying there with his breathing mask twisted out of its correct position.  He subsequently died in Visby Hospital. On 6 October the fire was deemed to be extinguished.
ShipType1: Ro-Ro Ship for timber and paper cargoes

SummaryOfEvents:
Shortly after berthing at West Swanson dock, Melbourne, 02 24 September 1993 the container and general cargo ship  “Iron Flinders”, on charter to BHP Ltd., suffered a fire in the waste-heat unit (economiser) which is situated in the main engine exhaust  trunking at the base of the funnel.
The fire gained sufficient hold for an hydrogen-iron fire to become established, and the internal tube banks of the unit were completely destroyed before the fire was extinguished some eight hours later by the Melbourne Metropolitan Fire Brigade, assisted by the ship’s staff and the use of over 8 tonnes of liquid carbon dioxide.

Location: Off the North-West Coast of Australia
SummaryOfEvents:
On 28 July 1993, the off-shore supply ship Maersk Runner was employed running out anchors for the mobile drilling unit Atwood Falcon in the Walkley-l field, on the Australian North-West Shelf. 
This operation involved the use of a 64 mm diameter working wire, or "chaser wire", which is used to haul the anchors out to the correct position and then to lower the anchors to the seabed. 
As a dedicated chaser wire had not been provided, the ship had been using the starboard, 70 mm towing wire. When this towing wire parted, early that morning, a composite chaser wire, made up from a number of wire pendants shackled together, was used. 
In the early part of the afternoon, one of the anchors failed to set in the seabed and had to be lifted and repositioned. As Maersk Runner started to lift this anchor, the composite chaser wire parted at a spelter socket, positioned just off the winch. The Mate was struck and thrown by flaying wire, suffering severe head and pelvic wounds, as a result of which he died.

Location: Off Green Island, Bona Vistan Newfoundland
SummaryOfEvents: On 05 July 1993, the 5.5 metre open fishing ship CFV 132145 capsized when struck broadside by a wave as a lobster trap was being reset. The three occupants, who were not wearing life Jackets or personal flotation devices, were thrown into the water. After the owner/operator had assisted his son and his grandson on to the overturned boat, he lost consciousness, was washed off the boat, which drifted to an island where they huddled in a rock crevice until rescued the next morning.

ShipType1: Other Bulk Dry (cement, woodchips, urea and other specialized) Carrier

SummaryOfEvents: While crossing Skidegate Narrows, British Columbia, the "Crown Forest 72-68" listed to starboard until the ship capsized. The crew of two was in the wheel-house. The operator escaped from the wheel-house and climbed on the capsized hull. He was unable to find his companion after a search above and below water. The operator was rescued a short time later. The body of the missing crew member was later recovered from the wheel-house by a diver but resuscitation attempts were unsuccessful.
ShipType1: Freglass, general purpose, cargo landing craft

SummaryOfEvents:
On 12 May 1993, the fully laden, 81,248 tonnes deadweight Bahamas flag tanker Oppama Spirit grounded at Gove, Northern Territory. The ship had been manoeuvring to go alongside the berth, when it experienced a total power loss as a result of the seawater cooling system becoming blocked. While under tow to the anchorage, the ship took a sheer and grounded forward. 
The ship was pulled clear by one of the tugs after less than one hour, and towed to the anchorage without further mishap. 
No damage was sustained by the ship and no oil pollution occurred as a result of the grounding.

The German flag, 35,303 gross tonnes container ship Berlin Express, while proceeding in auto-pilot steering mode through the dredged cut, in the South Channel, Port Phillip Bay, en route to Melbourne, took a rapid sheer to starboard, as a result of which the ship grounded adjacent to South Channel Pile beacon. 
Assisted by two tugs from the Port of Melbourne, the ship was successfully refloated 10 hours later, on the next high tide. 
The ship suffered no structural damage, and no pollution occurred as a result of the grounding.

SOLASStatus: GREEB LEAF: Unknown/unspecified, XIANG YANG HONG 16: Unknown/unspecified

SummaryOfEvents:
The Malinska, a Maltese flag bulk carrier of 34, 752 tonnes deadweight, loaded a full cargo of manganese ore at the Groote Eylandt loading terminal from 23 to 25 April 1993.

While sailing from the port, the ship, which should have cleared  via a narrow channel of deep water through a bank stretching southward from Connexion Island, grounded on Burley Shoal, 1.5 miles north of “the gap”. Initial attempts to refloat the ship were unsuccessful and 1100 tonnes of cargo had to be off-loaded before the ship was pulled off by tugs on 28 April 1993.

Le 19 Mars 1993, le « Ju Ju » faisait route vers le détroit de Kildidt (Colombie-Britannique) pour s’y abriter d’un coup de vent sud-est. Le bateau a fait eau sous les ponts et a coulé peu de temps après. Deux des trois membres de l’équipage ont été repêchés, souffrant d’hypothermie. Le troisième a succombé à l’hypothermie et s’est noyé avant d’être recueilli.

SummaryOfEvents: On the afternoon of 05 February 1993, passengers and vehicles were disembarking from the Queen of Burnaby in dock No 8 at Tsawwassen Terminal. The ferry’s main propulsion was in operation to hold the ship in position but, as the discharging procedure continued, the Queen of Burnaby became misaligned with the berth such that the shore ramp to the vehicle deck was partially supported by the hinged flaps at the end of the ramp apron. The flaps were pushed to the vertical by the deck edge, and a vehicle, which was driving off, struck them and was damaged.

Le cape Aspy a appareillé  de Luxemburg (Nouvelle-Ecosse) le 30 Janvier 1993 à destination des lieux de pêche  du banc Georges. Environ 14 heures plus tard, par gros temps, le navire a coulé en cours de route par 120 brasses de fond par 42°28.6 N et 65°58.2 W, faisant cinq morts.
Consequences1: Loss of life,Total loss of the ship

SOLASStatus: MAERSK NAVIGATOR: Unknown/unspecified, SANKO HONOUR: Unknown/unspecified
SummaryOfEvents:
On 20 Jan 1993 at 16:20 hours UTC, the second officer of MaerskNavigator took over the watch from the third officer. The Maersk Navigator was steering a course of 088°T and making good a speed of 11 knots. As the ship was on autopilot, the seaman designated as helmsman was acting as lookout.

At 18:00 hours UTC the second officer of Maersk Navigator detected 3 ships on the ARPA ali moving in the opposite direction. One ships which was later identified as the Sanko Honour was 2° to 3° on the starboard bow. The closest point of approach (CPA) of Sanko Honour was 0.5 mile. The Sanko Honour was sighted visually at a distance of 6.7 miles, fine on the
starboard bow. The second officer of Maersk Navigator altered course to increase the CPA to 0.9 mile. After the altération the Sanko Honour was sighted about 10° on the port
bow. At a range of about 4 miles, the Sanko Honour disappeared visually and from the radar due to heavy rain  squali. After re-adjusting the anti-rain clutter on the ARPA, Sanko Honour reappeared on the radar screen and was tracked again. Radar information indicated that Sanko Honor had altered course to port. Immediately, the second officer of Maersk Navigator put the helm on hard-to-starboard and steadied on a heading of 14 8°T. He then saw the Sanko Honour approaching from the port beam showing a green sidelight and ordered the helm hard-to-starboard and called the master. A short while later, the bow of the Sanko Honour collided with the port side of the Maersk Navigator.


On 20 Jan 1993 at 16:45 hours UTC, the second officer of Sanko Honour took over the watch from the third officer. One of the two 3 cm radars was in use and the ARPA was not in operation. The Sanko Honour was steering 268°T and making good a speed of 16.5 knots. There were two ships forward of her beam. Both ships were moving in the same direction with one ship on either side of her. The ship was on autopilot and the seaman on duty acted
as lookout. There was also a cadet keeping watch with the second officer. At 18:20 hours UTC the second officer of Sanko Honour detected one vessel on the radar screen at a range of
20 miles in the direction of 8° on the starboard bow. This ship was later identified as the Maersk Navigator. The second officer of Sanko Honour began systematic radar plot using the radar reflector plotter. At 18:35 hours UTC, the Maersk Navigator was at a range of 13 miles and 12° on the starboard bow. About this time, the second officer and the cadet sighted the two masthead lights and the green sidelight of Maersk Navigator, about 5° on the starboard bow. At the same time they sighted the port side ship showing the green sidelight and the second officer concluded that the overtaken ship had now became a crossing ship. He changed from automatic steering to manual and altered course to port. The cadet was at the wheel. After this, the Sanko Honour was caught in heavy rain squall and both targets disappeared from the radar screen. An attempt was made to recover both targets by adjusting the anti-rain clutter control and switching on the standby radar but was  nsuccessful. A visual check was made with the aid of binoculars but no ship was seen. At 18:43 hours UTC course was altered 10°to port to give more clearance to the ship being overtaken. Once on this heading, the ship was changed to automatic steering and the cadet was told to keep a lookout for the Maersk Navigator. The cadet saw the red sidelight of Maersk Navigator very close. At the same time the second officer also sighted the Maersk Navigator. Immediately he instructed the cadet to put the wheel on hard-to-port. As the ship was turning to port the Sanko Honour collided with the Maersk Navigator.

On 16 January 1993, while en route from Portland, OR, to Verdal, Norway, under tow by the tug Smit Singapore, the towline to freight barge GCC 700 parted during heavy weather off the coast of Norway. The barge drift ashore, grounded and sank. The barge was a constructive total loss.
